broadcast policy, but also considers significant recurring themes including the environment, the body, race and First Nations, and the North. Through critical analyses of key films and interviews conducted with filmmakers from all corners of the region, Varga uncovers patterns of meaning across diverse productions and interrogates the concept of region in relation to prevailing notions of national cinema and transnational media culture. With a focus on short films and an extensive history and analysis of the filmmaking production co-operatives located in each province, Shooting from the East sheds light on the creative processes and local economic and cultural conditions for making images on the edge of the Atlantic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picture industryxHistoryx20th centuryxAtlantic Provinces. 0aMotion picture industryzAtlantic ProvincesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picturesxHistoryxAtlantic Provinces. 0aMotion pictureszAtlantic ProvincesxHistory. 0aTelevision broadcastingxHistoryx20th centuryxAtlantic Provinces. 0aTelevision broadcastingzAtlantic ProvincesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTelevision programsxHistory and criticismxAtlantic Provinces. 0aTelevision programszAtlantic ProvincesxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359804140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773598041423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773598041/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-